column4: “… every form of agriculture is unknown…” (Birket-Smith 1930: 19); small quantities of wheat raised in “recent” (my) years (Curtis 1928: 24)
Permanent [underlined]; irrigation - obviously not; drinking [underlined] - ?; how about to catch beavers?; (not permanent)

(+); pack-dogs (Hearne 1795: 323); this question is mainly one of timing: both of these traits are there (+) but are recent – the ? is = how well integrated are they?; [* decision on 26+27 based on VanStone (1963: 24-25): women pulled sledges; dogs occasionally used for packing but venerated as ancestors]

(-); dog traction/sledges (Hearne 1795: 323); [* decision on 26+27 based on VanStone (1963: 24-25) women pulled sledges; dogs occasionally used for packing but venerated as ancestors]; people for traction thruout Tyrrell (1934); Franklin says no to dogs (Birket-Smith 1930: 40); this question is mainly one of timing: both of these traits are there (+) but are recent – the ? is = how well integrated are they?
dog drags sled in legend; dog traction introduced by Europ.
some dog traction, packing (Hearne 1795: 323); Dogs for packing and traction = relatively new (Curtis 1928: 32)
but at least 40% of the  year
[including houses along the shore]; “in camp the tents stand in apparently unarranged order”; however, in one source there is a diagram which shows horse shoe arrangement of “village”
no numbers of people given; Mackenzie (1801: CXVII) = it is impossible to estimate their number; five families in band[x?]
no burial (VanStone 1963: 54); now, yes. not before.; expose corpses w/ their property (Curtis 1928: 44)
I would think they’d be satisfied w/ naturally collected water
no property holding systém (Curtis 1928: 41); see Birket-Smith (1930: 69 [paragraph 2?]) under customary law
(how about the male/female specialties, does this count?)
(+); communities [underlined] - no?; Trade has “now” ceased w/ Dogrib, Yellow Knife; now w/ Eskimos
Economically important [underlined] - the society could not readily get along without the commodities traded; not sure of this – again a ? of timing
neither religious nor fraternal societies, no tribal ceremonies…
Marriages are not attended by any ceremony
only Matonabbee (a chief) was reported as having 8 wives

chief – most capable hunter, fighter, leader (Curtis (1928: 43); “… everything would seem to indicate that their authority was entirely based on their personality …. Real political exercising of power is scarcely credible” (Birket-Smith 1930: 66)
(-); bilateral k-ship; chiefs position depends solely on hunting skill and his influence extends only to matters of hunting – so this trait is unlikely
all corpses exposed -> more important men in tipis rather than outside
(+); One chief had 8 wives: Matonabee; if he’s the best hunter he can support significantly more
negative, I think; Murderer is shunned by kin + friends (Hearne 1795: 108)
negative, I think; there is no incest (Hearne 1795: 130)
(+); Extermination; Hearne (1795: 338-339 fn.) –; for stone kettles from Eskimos (Tyrrell 1934: 551); when they felt superior in numbers to the enemy (Birket-Smith 1930: 35)
no; sneak up on Eskimos and destroy them in their sleep; plunder
Reckless, headlong attack (Curtis 1928: 10); no pitched battle (Hearne 1795: 355)
spears (Hearne 1795: 152); spears (for caribou) or fighting at close quarters (Curtis 1928: 28); hatchets (Birket-Smith 1930: 35)
no prisoners (Hearne 1795: 340 fn.); slaughter all enemies
rely on “imaginary beings which inhabit the element”, for success in battle
bad soul does not reach the island where the realm of the dead is; his stone canoe sinks and he stands in water up to his neck
(-); Religious specialists [underlined]; Birket-Smith (1930: 73-74) doesn’t mention; check frequency; (difference betw. relig. specialist and priest)
see Birket-Smith (1930: 78); I don’t think so
I don’t think it was mentioned
boards sewn (Hearne 1795: 324); Curtis (1928: 33) quotes Hearne (1795): boards sewn together
just camp stove, mosquito nets = recent

“ropes of hare fur w/ cord weft” (Curtis 1928: 25); “leather and fur were the sole materials for garments, and the favorite robe was … made by weaving ropes of hare-fur on a warp of caribou-skin cord” (Curtis 1928: 29)
(+); Fabrics [underlined]; embroidery [underlined]; clothing is ornamented, but it is not fabric but hide (Curtis 1928: 26)
(-); used [underlined] - ? - does this imply that they were made, but by others; unworked  copper nugget suspended from neck
some canoe makers are better than others
“… utterly unacquainted w/ letters, or the use of hieroglyphics…”
they add up points of ring-and-pin game
see “rounders” game in Birket-Smith (1930: 71); “udzi” - 2 sets of men, coop. is questionable (Curtis 1928: 37)
they have no midwives, and “scoff at the idea”
